{{italic title}}
[[File:Emporer Frederic I death.jpg|thumb|The death of [[Frederick Barbarossa]] as depicted in the Gotha manuscript of the ''Sächsische Weltchronik'']]
The '''''Sächsische Weltchronik''''' ("Saxon World Chronicle") is a [[universal history]] written in vernacular [[German language|German]] prose between 1229 and 1277. The twenty-four surviving manuscripts are a mix of [[Middle Low German|Low German]] (ten), [[Middle High German|High German]] (nine) and [[Central German]] (five). The 98-line verse prologue is always in High German. The ''Weltchronik'' is the oldest historical work in German prose.{{sfn|Kries|1987|p=448–49|ps=. The ''[[Kaiserchronik]]'' is earlier, but in verse. The ''Weltchronik'' of [[Rudolf von Ems]] is contemporary, but also verse.}} Ludwig Weiland, who made a critical edition for the [[Monumenta Germaniae Historica]] in 1877, gave it the conventional title by which it is most commonly known.<ref>MGH ''Deutsche Chroniken'' '''2''' (Hanover: Hahn, 1877).</ref> The [[Editio princeps|first edition]] was prepared by [[Hans Ferdinand Massmann]] in 1857, but was based on only one manuscript.<ref>Massmann titled his work ''Das Zeitbuch des Eike von Repkow'' (Stuttgart).</ref> The manuscripts are classified into three [[recensions]]—A, B and C—and the oldest group (A) is entirely High German.{{sfn|Kries|1987|pp=449–50}} Michael Menzel classifies a fifteenth-century manuscript from [[Wolfenbüttel]] as the ''[[Leittext]]''.{{sfn|Kries|1987|pp=449–50}}

It was once thought that the ''Weltchronik'' might be the work of [[Eike of Repgow]], the author of the ''[[Sachsenspiegel]]'' (a Low German work on law), but this hypothesis—which depended in part on the assumption that the original work was Low German—has been abandoned.{{sfn|Kries|1987|pp=449–50}} The author employed at least thirty-six different [[Middle Latin|Latin]] chronicles in his research. The most important were the ''Chronicle'' of [[Frutolf of Michelsberg]], the continuation of the same by [[Ekkehard of Aura]] and the ''[[Annales Palidenses]]''.{{sfn|Kries|1987|pp=449–50}}

